<p id="p0225">The BO approximation is violated for the electron energy in the second order of perturbation theory and for the electron wave function in the first order of perturbation theory. It can be seen that the nonadiabatic corrections 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M86" altimg="si73.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msubsup>
     <mrow>
      <mi>V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>f</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">(</mo>
       <mrow>
        <mn>2</mn>
       </mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">)</mo>
      </mrow>
     </mrow>
    </msubsup>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> from 
 <xref rid="fd17" ref-type="disp-formula">Eq. (17)</xref> and 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M87" altimg="si74.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msubsup>
     <mrow>
      <mi>ψ</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>f</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">(</mo>
       <mrow>
        <mn>1</mn>
       </mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">)</mo>
      </mrow>
     </mrow>
    </msubsup>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> from 
 <xref rid="fd18" ref-type="disp-formula">Eq. (18)</xref> are not minor in the case when the differences of the electronic terms 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M88" altimg="si75.svg">
   <mrow>
    <msubsup>
     <mrow>
      <mi>V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>f</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">(</mo>
       <mrow>
        <mn>0</mn>
       </mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">)</mo>
      </mrow>
     </mrow>
    </msubsup>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak" linebreakstyle="after">−</mo>
    <msubsup>
     <mrow>
      <mi>V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <msup>
       <mi>f</mi>
       <mo>′</mo>
      </msup>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">(</mo>
       <mrow>
        <mn>0</mn>
       </mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">)</mo>
      </mrow>
     </mrow>
    </msubsup>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, which depend on the nuclear coordinates 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M89" altimg="si51.svg">
   <mrow>
    <mi>p</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and which enter into the denominators, turn out to be small.
</p>
